{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-ad3ab2327fcffe58", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t Probing Low-Level Acoustic Attribute Encoding in CLAP Audio Embeddings Report GitHub Issue × Title: Content selection saved. Describe the issue below: Description: Submit without GitHub Submit in \n2\tGitHub arXiv is now an independent nonprofit! Learn more × Back to arXiv Why HTML? Report Issue Back to Abstract Download PDF Abstract 1 Introduction 2 Methodology 2.1 Target Acoustic Attributes 2.2 \n3\tProbe Models 2.3 Evaluation Metrics 3 Experimental settings 3.1 Datasets 3.2 Feature Generation 3.3 Training Details 4 Results 4.1 Feature Axis Analysis 4.2 Effect of Training Set Size 4.3 \n4\tGeneralization to Other Models 4.4 Text-based Attribute Prediction 5 Conclusion References License: CC BY 4.0 arXiv:2607.03806v1 [eess.AS] 04 Jul 2026 Probing Low-Level Acoustic Attribute Encoding in \n5\tCLAP Audio Embeddings Abstract Audio foundation models are widely adopted as general-purpose feature extractors, yet the internal structure of their learned representations remains insufficiently \n6\tunderstood. In this work, we analyze CLAP audio embeddings through a probing framework, studying the encoding of three fundamental perceptual dimensions: reverberation (RT60), loudness (LUFS), and \n7\tspectral content, measured via spectral centroid (SC) and relative pitch (RP). Probes of increasing complexity are trained to predict each attribute from frozen embeddings across five datasets \n8\tspanning noise, speech, monophonic musical notes, and music mixtures. Our primary finding is that all of these attributes are reliably recoverable from the CLAP embedding space across the examined \n9\tdatasets. Within this global picture, two encoding regimes emerge: RT60, LUFS, and RP are approximately linearly encoded, while SC requires non-linear probes. Both regimes generalize across eight \n10\tadditional audio foundation models, with the notable exception that amplitude-invariant architectures discard loudness entirely by construction. The identified linear feature directions are \n11\tgeometrically consistent across datasets for RT60 and LUFS, while highly domain-specific for RP. Finally, we provide a qualitative demonstration of cross-modal consistency, showing that text \n12\tembeddings of acoustic descriptors align geometrically with the identified RT60 feature direction. 1 Introduction CLAP [ 11 , 12 ] is a prominent audio-language foundation model that leverages \n13\tcontrastive learning to align audio and text in a shared embedding space. Trained on large collections of audio-text pairs, CLAP learns embeddings that capture both acoustic characteristics and \n14\tsemantic content, enabling applications such as audio retrieval, captioning [ 39 , 20 ] , audio quality assessment [ 9 , 6 ] , effect parameter estimation [ 5 ] , room impulse response synthesis [ 31 \n15\t] , and conditional audio generation [ 19 , 36 , 16 ] . The model has since been extended to incorporate temporal [ 38 ] and stereo [ 29 ] information. Despite this widespread adoption, the internal \n16\trepresentation structure of CLAP remains insufficiently understood. Probing studies of audio-language models have largely examined specific domains or model classes: early work probed speech \n17\tembeddings for speaker and phonetic information [ 26 ] , while more recent analyses of Large Audio-Language Models (LALMs), a model class that does not encompass CLAP, probe high-level perceptual \n18\tattributes such as language, gender, and emotion of speech [ 35 , 4 ] . Interpretability approaches for acoustic models have favored qualitative concept alignment [ 32 ] over quantitative prediction \n19\tof physical descriptors. Within the CLAP literature, studies have shown that high-level features such as timbre [ 7 ] and emotion [ 30 ] are effectively captured. However, low-level acoustic \n20\tattributes have received far less attention. [ 8 ] shows that applying audio effects at varying intensities traces consistent trajectories in the CLAP embedding space. The authors exploit this \n21\tproperty to improve embedding robustness. Conversely, FXEncoder++ [ 37 ] learns representations that capture audio effects independently of content. Text2FX [ 5 ] uses CLAP embeddings for audio \n22\teffect parameter estimation via text prompts, implicitly assuming high cross-modal alignment and encoding of sufficient detail for fine-grained acoustic manipulation. In contrast, [ 6 ] proposes an \n23\tAcoustic Context (ACX) Representation for audio quality enhancement and argues that CLAP embeddings fail to quantify noise or reverberation. These mixed findings leave a central question open: which \n24\tlow-level acoustic attributes are encoded in CLAP embeddings, and how readily can they be recovered? Our work aims to address this gap through a systematic probing study. Figure 1: Overview of the \n25\tprobing methodology. 2 Methodology An overview of the probing methodology is presented in Figure 1 . Each waveform [MATH] , with [MATH] channels and [MATH] samples, is transformed with an \n26\tattribute-dependent data augmentation and downmixed to mono obtaining [MATH] . [MATH] is then encoded into [MATH] ( [MATH] ), which serves as the sole input to all probes. The probes produce the \n27\tpredictions for single scalar attributes [MATH] and are trained on regression against the ground truth values [MATH] used during the augmentation process. The encoder is kept fully frozen: all \n28\tlearned parameters belong exclusively to the probe models. We use the audio encoder from LAION-CLAP [ 33 , 2 ] checkpoint trained on speech, music, AudioSet, and LAION-Audio-630k 1 1 1 laion-clap : \n29\thttps://github.com/LAION-AI/CLAP , selected for its broad coverage across audio domains. 2.1 Target Acoustic Attributes We investigate the encoding of low-level acoustic attributes in the CLAP \n30\tembedding space, covering three fundamental perceptual dimensions: room acoustics, perceived loudness, and spectral content. All attributes are defined and computable across all datasets regardless \n31\tof audio domain or musical instrumentation. Reverberation Time (RT60). RT60 measures the time required for sound energy to decay by 60 dB following the cessation of a source, and is one of the most \n32\tcommon descriptors of room acoustic conditions [ 28 ] . It is used here as a global measure of the degree of reverberation present in an audio sample, ranging from near-zero values in anechoic or \n33\tclose-miked recordings to several seconds in reverberant spaces. Loudness (LUFS). Signal loudness is computed as integrated loudness following the ITU-R BS.1770 standard [ 18 ] , using the pyloudnorm \n34\tlibrary 2 2 2 pyloudnorm : https://github.com/csteinmetz1/pyloudnorm . Unlike peak amplitude or RMS energy, integrated LUFS accounts for frequency-dependent loudness perception, making it the de \n35\tfacto standard for loudness normalization in broadcast and music production. Spectral Centroid (SC). The SC is the center of mass of the magnitude spectrum, [MATH] , where [MATH] denotes the index of \n36\tthe frequency bin, [MATH] the corresponding frequency, and [MATH] its STFT magnitude [ 23 ] . We compute SC per frame from the STFT magnitude using a Hann window of length 2048 and hop size 512 \n37\tsamples, and then average across frames. We employ the SC rather than the fundamental frequency [MATH] because it is well-defined for complex audio mixtures such as full songs, for which [MATH] \n38\testimation is unreliable or ill-posed. Relative Pitch (RP). The RP re-expresses SC on a logarithmic semitone scale as [MATH] , with [MATH] Hz (A4), following the standard equal-tempered tuning \n39\trelationship between frequency and pitch [ 17 , 23 ] . RP and SC probe the same underlying spectral property from complementary scales, allowing us to assess whether encoding linearity depends on the \n40\tscale used. 2.2 Probe Models We evaluate three probe architectures of increasing complexity. All are intentionally lightweight so that performance differences reflect the embedding space rather than \n41\tprobe capacity. Linear Probe. A single affine map [MATH] , with [MATH] parameters. The weight vector [MATH] defines the feature axis : the single direction in embedding space most predictive of the \n42\ttarget. Strong performance indicates linear decodability, while poor performance indicates the need for non-linear encoding. MLP Probe. A two-layer network [MATH] with [MATH] hidden dimensions ( \n43\t[MATH] 32.9k parameters). Shallow enough to avoid memorization, it captures non-linear relationships that the linear probe cannot. The MLP–Linear gap quantifies encoding non-linearity. Kernel \n44\tProbe. Kernel Ridge Regression (KRR) with an Radial Basis Function (RBF) kernel [ 27 ] [MATH] , [MATH] . Predictions are given by [MATH] , where [MATH] solves the [MATH] system [MATH] , with [MATH] \n45\tthe target values for the [MATH] selected examples, and [MATH] . [MATH] is capped at [MATH] randomly selected examples for tractability (KRR scales as [MATH] ). Embeddings are L2-normalized before \n46\tfitting. Since [MATH] for unit vectors, the cosine RBF [MATH] becomes the effective kernel. KRR makes no parametric assumptions and serves as a flexible non-linear reference without gradient-based \n47\toptimisation sensitivity, providing an approximate ceiling for non-linear probe performance. 2.3 Evaluation Metrics Probes are evaluated using three complementary metrics. Mean Absolute Error (MAE) \n48\tmeasures prediction error in the original unit of each feature, [MATH] . It is directly interpretable but scale-dependent, preventing comparison across features with different units or dynamic \n49\tranges. Coefficient of Determination ( [MATH] ) is the proportion of target variance explained by the model, [MATH] . [MATH] is a perfect fit, [MATH] matches a constant mean predictor, and negative \n50\tvalues indicate worse-than-trivial performance. Unlike MAE, it is scale-free and accounts for task difficulty via the target variance. Pearson Correlation ( [MATH] ) measures the linear association \n51\tbetween predictions and ground truth, [MATH] . Being insensitive to affine transformations, it is complementary to [MATH] : a high [MATH] with low [MATH] indicates correct direction but miscalibrated \n52\tscale. Conversely, a negative [MATH] indicates an encoding failure, as the probe recovers the attribute in the wrong direction on held-out data. 3 Experimental settings 3.1 Datasets To test \n53\tgeneralization across domains, we evaluate probes on five datasets spanning noise, speech, and music at increasing complexity, from monophonic notes to full music mixtures. All audio is resampled to \n54\t48 kHz to match the sample rate of LAION-CLAP. White Noise (100k samples) is a synthetic control of generated white noise samples of 10 seconds each with constant amplitude envelope. Since all \n55\tsamples share the same flat spectral shape and carry no musical or semantic content, all variation in the embeddings is driven exclusively by the applied augmentation, making it the most controlled \n56\tsetting in our evaluation and serving as an upper bound on what a purely acoustic signal can encode. Labels are generated synthetically as described in Sec. 3.2 . NSynth [ 13 ] (306k samples) \n57\tcontains monophonic notes from 1,006 instruments at 16 kHz, spanning the full MIDI pitch range (21–108) at five velocity levels. Each sample is a 4-second clip in which a single note is held for \n58\tthree seconds and decays over the final second. It represents the simplest scenario in our evaluation, with a single note isolated from rhythmic or harmonic context. VCTK-Corpus [ 34 ] (44k samples) \n59\tis a speech dataset containing recordings from 110 English speakers with diverse accents. The recordings are clean, studio-quality speech with minimal background noise, making them well-suited for \n60\tisolating acoustic attributes in our study. MusDB18HQ [ 25 ] (34k samples) is a music source separation dataset containing 150 songs at 44.1 kHz. We use the full additive mix, segmented into \n61\t10-second chunks with 1-second overlap. To avoid data leakage, the training, validation, and test sets are split by song. MusDB18HQ represents a more complex musical scenario than NSynth, with \n62\tmultiple instruments, polyphony, and realistic production arrangements. The mixes are raw recordings without compression, equalization, or mastering, making low-level acoustic attributes directly \n63\tobservable. SonicMaster [ 22 ] (525k samples) comprises songs across 10 balanced genre groups. The dataset contains ground truth mastered tracks and degraded versions with applied audio effects (e.g. \n64\tequalization, dynamics). We consider only the ground truth mastered tracks and split them by song to ensure no data leakage. This dataset represents the most production-realistic and largest-scale \n65\tscenario in our benchmark. For all datasets, targets are measured as per Sec. 3.2 and we use 80%/10%/10% splits for training, validation, and testing. The splits of VCTK and NSynth are \n66\tspeaker-disjoint and instrument-disjoint, respectively. 3.2 Feature Generation To ensure that each acoustic attribute spans a balanced distribution of values across its perceptually relevant range, \n67\tthe original datasets are augmented by applying a single targeted perturbation per sample. The embedding and attribute value are then computed from the perturbed signal. Each attribute is augmented \n68\tindependently (i.e., only one perturbation is applied per sample) so that attributes such as RT60 and LUFS cannot co-vary as a result of the augmentation procedure, and any correlation between their \n69\tlearned probe directions reflects embedding structure rather than a data pipeline confound. Following this regime we generate a full copy of each dataset per attribute. RT60: A target reverberation \n70\ttime is uniformly sampled as [MATH] s. A synthetic room impulse response (RIR) is generated using gpuRIR 3 3 3 gpuRIR : https://github.com/DavidDiazGuerra/gpuRIR . Room dimensions are sampled \n71\tuniformly per axis in [MATH] m, and wall reflection coefficients are derived analytically from [MATH] via the Sabine equation [ 10 ] . The RIR is convolved with the dry waveform, and the output is \n72\tRMS-normalized to the level of the input to prevent loudness from acting as a proxy cue for RT60. LUFS: A target loudness level is uniformly sampled as [MATH] LUFS. The signal is then normalized to \n73\t[MATH] using the loudness normalization function provided by pyloudnorm , ensuring that the training distribution covers a wide and balanced range of perceived loudness levels. SC: Two procedures are \n74\tused depending on the dataset. For White Noise, a target SC value is sampled as [MATH] Hz and the noise is filtered with a bandpass filter centered at [MATH] with a bandwidth drawn from [MATH] \n75\toctaves, controlling the spectral center of mass. For all other datasets, a fractional pitch shift [MATH] semitones is uniformly sampled and applied to the waveform via the torch_audiomentations 4 4 \n76\t4 torch_audiomentations : https://github.com/iver56/torch-audiomentations phase vocoder. This creates a smooth distribution of pitch in all datasets, breaking the quantised structures present in \n77\tmusic datasets (e.g. NSynth contains only integer pitch values, which we found to hinder regression performance). The two strategies are not interchangeable by design: bandpass filtering is \n78\tappropriate only for spectrally flat signals, while pitch shifting preserves content. Since probes are always trained and evaluated within the same dataset, no transfer across augmentation strategies \n79\tis assumed or performed. In both cases, the SC is computed as defined in Sec. 2.1 using the SpectralCentroid transform from torchaudio 5 5 5 torchaudio : https://github.com/pytorch/audio , yielding a \n80\tsingle scalar in Hz. RP: No additional augmentation is applied for RP. The attribute value is obtained from the SC value following the method described in Sec. 2.1 . 3.3 Training Details The Linear \n81\tand MLP probes are trained for 100 epochs with a batch size of 256 to minimize the MSE objective with AdamW optimizer, using a learning rate of [MATH] and weight decay of [MATH] . Early stopping is \n82\tapplied based on the validation loss, with a patience of 10 epochs. The Kernel probe is fitted in a single training iteration. For the largest dataset (SonicMaster), results were verified to be \n83\tstable when increasing [MATH] from [MATH] to [MATH] , confirming the cap does not constrain performance. All reported results are averaged over 10 independent runs with different random seeds. 4 \n84\tResults Table 1: Test-set probing results across datasets, averaged over 10 independent seeds. Bold indicates the best or joint-best result per (dataset, feature). [MATH] : probe failure ( [MATH] ); \n85\tnegative [MATH] values above this threshold are reported explicitly. Standard deviations of [MATH] across seeds are [MATH] for RT60 and LUFS, [MATH] for SC (MLP and Kernel only, as Linear probe fails \n86\ton SC), and [MATH] for RP. White Noise NSynth VCTK-Corpus Musdb18HQ SonicMaster Feature Probe MAE [MATH] [MATH] [MATH] [MATH] [MATH] MAE [MATH] [MATH] [MATH] [MATH] [MATH] MAE [MATH] [MATH] [MATH] \n87\t[MATH] [MATH] MAE [MATH] [MATH] [MATH] [MATH] [MATH] MAE [MATH] [MATH] [MATH] [MATH] [MATH] RT60 Linear 0.09 0.95 0.98 0.25 0.67 0.82 0.12 0.92 0.96 0.21 0.77 0.88 0.21 0.76 0.87 MLP 0.07 0.97 0.99 \n88\t0.21 0.75 0.87 0.10 0.94 0.97 0.20 0.79 0.89 0.19 0.80 0.89 Kernel 0.04 0.99 1.00 0.18 0.81 0.90 0.09 0.95 0.98 0.21 0.75 0.88 0.19 0.79 0.89 LUFS Linear 0.5 0.99 1.00 3.0 0.80 0.90 2.1 0.92 0.96 3.5 \n89\t0.76 0.88 2.1 0.90 0.95 MLP 0.3 1.00 1.00 2.2 0.89 0.95 1.5 0.95 0.98 2.1 0.90 0.95 1.4