ke RT60 and \n129\tLUFS, whose global transformations leave a partially consistent trace across domains, the RP axis is dominated by domain-specific embedding structure and does not transfer across speech, isolated \n130\tnotes, noise, and music, even though RP is well-encoded and linearly recoverable within each domain individually. Figure 3 illustrates what projecting onto a linear probe weight vector looks like in \n131\tpractice, using VCTK-Corpus as a representative dataset. Each embedding of the test set is projected onto the scalar [MATH] and plotted against its ground-truth value. 4.2 Effect of Training Set Size \n132\tTo understand how probe performance scales with the amount of training data, we train Linear probes on progressively smaller subsets of SonicMaster and measure performance as a function of training \n133\tset size. SonicMaster is chosen for this study as it is the largest and most domain-diverse dataset in our benchmark, making it a suitable basis for a data efficiency analysis. SC is excluded since \n134\tthe Linear probe fails at all training sizes. The Linear probe is used here by design: with only [MATH] parameters, its saturation curve directly reflects the sample complexity of estimating a single \n135\tdirection in the embedding space, without confounds from probe capacity or gradient-based optimisation sensitivity that would arise with the MLP or Kernel probes. Table 2: Linear probe test-set MAE / \n136\t[MATH] on SonicMaster at varying training-set sizes (val/test splits always use the full set). [MATH] : probe failure ( [MATH] ); negative [MATH] values above this threshold are reported explicitly. \n137\tSC is omitted as the Linear probe fails at all sizes. Pearson [MATH] is omitted from this and the following table as it is monotonically related to [MATH] on a fixed test set. RT60 LUFS RP Ratio \n138\t[MATH] MAE [MATH] MAE [MATH] MAE [MATH] 0.01 4.2 0.22 0.73 17.6 [MATH] 22.6 [MATH] 0.02 8.4 0.22 0.75 5.7 0.34 6.5 [MATH] 0.71 0.05 2