{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-88e82a29d8b68bc0", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# Auden-Voice: General-Purpose Voice Encoder for Speech and Language Understanding\narXiv: 2511.15145\nAuthors: Mingyue Huo, Wei-Cheng Tseng, Yiwen Shao, Hao Zhang, Dong Yu\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. ASR initialization provides a strong inductive bias that consistently improves voice representation learning across identity and paralinguistic tasks compared to training from scratch.\n  2. Multi-task supervision yields the most balanced voice representations across both identity and paralinguistic cues, whereas single-task supervision creates task-specific trade-offs.\n  3. CLAP fine-tuning consistently enhances speech-text retrieval but unexpectedly degrades linear probing, zero-shot speaker tasks, and zero-shot paralinguistic classification.\n  4. Scaling CLAP training data shows a partial trend toward recovering lost paralinguistic capabilities but still falls short of pre-CLAP performance levels.\n  5. LLM question-answering performance correlates strongly with linear probing results, demonstrating that stronger supervised representations translate to better acoustic grounding for LLM reasoning.\n  6. The multi-task encoder proves more effective than the multi-task+CLAP encoder for grounding LLM reasoning, leading to the final Auden-voice model.\n  7. The proposed Auden-voice encoder achieves competitive performance against end-to-end and cascade baselines, establishing a strong general-purpose voice encoder for LLM integration.\n\nTags: SSL, SSL/对比式, LALM, LALM/理解型", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "978ba9bf-23e0-4dc1-86a9-0fe72e55523f", "uuid": "73a86b98-9a4d-4716-b594-338373b955a2", "timestamp": "2026-07-12T11:24:25.642Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# Auden-Voice: General-Purpose Voice Encoder for Speech and Language Understanding\narXiv: 2511.15145\nAuthors: Mingyue Huo, Wei-Cheng Tseng, Yiwen Shao, Hao Zhang, Dong Yu\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. ASR initialization provides a strong inductive bias that consistently improves voice representation learning across identity and paralinguistic tasks compared to training from scratch.\n  2. Multi-task supervision yields the most balanced voice representations across both identity and paralinguistic cues, whereas single-task supervision creates task-specific trade-offs.\n  3. CLAP fine-tuning consistently enhances speech-text retrieval but unexpectedly degrades linear probing, zero-shot speaker tasks, and zero-shot paralinguistic classification.\n  4. Scaling CLAP training data shows a partial trend toward recovering lost paralinguistic capabilities but still falls short of pre-CLAP performance levels.\n  5. LLM question-answering performance correlates strongly with linear probing results, demonstrating that stronger supervised representations translate to better acoustic grounding for LLM reasoning.\n  6. The multi-task encoder proves more effective than the multi-task+CLAP encoder for grounding LLM reasoning, leading to the final Auden-voice model.\n  7. The proposed Auden-voice encoder achieves competitive performance against end-to-end and cascade baselines, establishing a strong general-purpose voice encoder for LLM integration.\n\nTags: SSL, SSL/对比式, LALM, LALM/理解型", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
