{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-9975f6b14fd29e57", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# WavJEPA: Semantic learning unlocks robust audio foundation models for raw waveforms\narXiv: 2509.23238\nAuthors: Goksenin Yuksel, Pierre Guetschel, Michael Tangermann, Marcel van Gerven, Kiki van der Heijden\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. WavJEPA introduces a waveform-based Joint-Embedding Predictive Architecture for general-purpose audio representation learning from raw waveforms.\n  2. This approach substantially outperforms state-of-the-art time-domain audio foundation models across various downstream benchmarks while requiring considerably fewer computational resources.\n  3. The framework leverages high-level semantic representation learning to overcome the limitations of token-level or speech unit-level representation learning.\n  4. WavJEPA-Nat is presented as a multi-channel extension of WavJEPA trained on simulated naturalistic scenes to handle noisy and reverberant real-world acoustic environments.\n  5. WavJEPA-Nat demonstrates high robustness to reverberation and noise, exceeding the robustness of other time-domain foundation models.\n  6. Extensive ablation studies elucidate the critical factors for semantic representation learning from raw waveforms, including context-target sampling, top-K averaging, and the optimal ratio of real-world scenes to dry sound clips.\n\nTags: SSL, SSL/预测式-离散", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "978ba9bf-23e0-4dc1-86a9-0fe72e55523f", "uuid": "65881c0c-6d8d-492a-8ee2-14693b1014fe", "timestamp": "2026-07-12T11:25:25.275Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# WavJEPA: Semantic learning unlocks robust audio foundation models for raw waveforms\narXiv: 2509.23238\nAuthors: Goksenin Yuksel, Pierre Guetschel, Michael Tangermann, Marcel van Gerven, Kiki van der Heijden\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. WavJEPA introduces a waveform-based Joint-Embedding Predictive Architecture for general-purpose audio representation learning from raw waveforms.\n  2. This approach substantially outperforms state-of-the-art time-domain audio foundation models across various downstream benchmarks while requiring considerably fewer computational resources.\n  3. The framework leverages high-level semantic representation learning to overcome the limitations of token-level or speech unit-level representation learning.\n  4. WavJEPA-Nat is presented as a multi-channel extension of WavJEPA trained on simulated naturalistic scenes to handle noisy and reverberant real-world acoustic environments.\n  5. WavJEPA-Nat demonstrates high robustness to reverberation and noise, exceeding the robustness of other time-domain foundation models.\n  6. Extensive ablation studies elucidate the critical factors for semantic representation learning from raw waveforms, including context-target sampling, top-K averaging, and the optimal ratio of real-world scenes to dry sound clips.\n\nTags: SSL, SSL/预测式-离散", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-9db27dff65e91e19", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# Rethinking Masking Strategies for Masked Prediction-based Audio Self-supervised Learning\narXiv: 2603.23810\nAuthors: Daisuke Niizumi, Daiki Takeuchi, Masahiro Yasuda, Binh Thien Nguyen, Noboru Harada, Nobutaka Ono\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We clarify the impact of masking strategies on audio spectrogram-based representation learning, highlighting their effects across different downstream tasks.\n  2. We propose DWM, a lightweight masking strategy tailored to audio spectrograms, which leverages dispersion patterns with minimal additional computational cost.\n\nTags: SSL, SSL/预测式-离散", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "978ba9bf-23e0-4dc1-86a9-0fe72e55523f", "uuid": "6e36fe7a-3644-403a-925b-4213af9e21c7", "timestamp": "2026-07-12T11:25:25.493Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# Rethinking Masking Strategies for Masked Prediction-based Audio Self-supervised Learning\narXiv: 2603.23810\nAuthors: Daisuke Niizumi, Daiki Takeuchi, Masahiro Yasuda, Binh Thien Nguyen, Noboru Harada, Nobutaka Ono\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We clarify the impact of masking strategies on audio spectrogram-based representation learning, highlighting their effects across different downstream tasks.\n  2. We propose DWM, a lightweight masking strategy tailored to audio spectrograms, which leverages dispersion patterns with minimal additional computational cost.\n\nTags: SSL, SSL/预测式-离散", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
