{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8f6ebf4ee89eb3ab", "type": "tool_result", "content": "      <h5 id=\"modal-title\" class=\"modal-title\">Report GitHub Issue</h5>\n      <button type=\"submit\" value=\"internal-report\" class=\"sr-only modal-submit\">Submit without GitHub</button>\n      <button type=\"submit\" value=\"github-report\" class=\"modal-submit\">Submit in GitHub</button>\n  <a id=\"license-tr\" href=\"https://info.arxiv.org/help/license/index.html#licenses-available\">\nWithin this global picture, two encoding regimes emerge: RT60, LUFS, and RP are approximately linearly encoded, while SC requires non-linear probes.\nProbing studies of audio-language models have largely examined specific domains or model classes: early work probed speech embeddings for speaker and phonetic information </span><cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\"><span id=\"S1.p2.1.2.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">[</span><a href=\"#bib.bib36\" title=\"Probing the information encoded in x-vectors\" class=\"ltx_ref\">26</a><span id=\"S1.p2.1.3.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">]</span></cite><span id=\"S1.p2.1.4\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">, while more recent analyses of Large Audio-Language Models (LALMs), a model class that does not encompass CLAP, probe high-level perceptual attributes such as language, gender, and emotion of speech </span><cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\"><span id=\"S1.p2.1.5.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">[</span><a href=\"#bib.bib38\" title=\"AudioLens: a closer look at auditory attribute perception of large audio-language models\" class=\"ltx_ref\">35</a>, <a href=\"#bib.bib39\" title=\"Causal tracing of audio-text fusion in large audio language models\" class=\"ltx_ref\">4</a><span id=\"S1.p2.1.6.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">]</span></cite><span id=\"S1.p2.1.7\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">.\nWithin the CLAP literature, studies have shown that high-level features such as timbre </span><cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\"><span id=\"S1.p2.1.11.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">[</span><a href=\"#bib.bib22\" title=\"Do joint language-audio embeddings encode perceptual timbre semantics?\" class=\"ltx_ref\">7</a><span id=\"S1.p2.1.12.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">]</span></cite><span id=\"S1.p2.1.13\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> and emotion </span><cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\"><span id=\"S1.p2.1.14.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">[</span><a href=\"#bib.bib30\" title=\"Evaluating foundation models on timbre-related cognitive tasks\" class=\"ltx_ref\">30</a><span id=\"S1.p2.1.15.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">]</span></cite><span id=\"S1.p2.1.16\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> are effectively captured. However, low-level acoustic attributes have received far less attention.\nConversely, FXEncoder++ </span><cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\"><span id=\"S1.p2.1.20.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">[</span><a href=\"#bib.bib8\" title=\"Fx-encoder++: extracting instrument-wise audio effects representations from mixtures\" class=\"ltx_ref\">37</a><span id=\"S1.p2.1.21.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">]</span></cite><span id=\"S1.p2.1.22\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> learns representations that capture audio effects independently of content.\n<p id=\"S1.p3.1\" class=\"ltx_p\"><span id=\"S1.p3.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">These mixed findings leave a central question open: which low-level acoustic attributes are encoded in CLAP embeddings, and how readily can they be recovered?\nEach waveform </span><math id=\"S2.p1.1.m1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"\\mathbf{x}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{C\\times T}\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">𝐱</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">∈</mo><msup><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">ℝ</mi><mrow><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">C</mi><mo lspace=\"0.222em\" mathsize=\"0.900em\" rspace=\"0.222em\">×</mo><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">T</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{x}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{C\\times T}</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.3\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">, with </span><math id=\"S2.p1.2.m2\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"C\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">C</mi><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.4\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> channels and </span><math id=\"S2.p1.3.m3\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"T\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">T</mi><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.5\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> samples, is transformed with an attribute-dependent data augmentation and downmixed to mono obtaining </span><math id=\"S2.p1.4.m4\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"\\mathbf{x^{\\prime}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{1\\times T}\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">𝐱</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">′</mo></msup><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">∈</mo><msup><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">ℝ</mi><mrow><mn mathsize=\"0.900em\">1</mn><mo lspace=\"0.222em\" mathsize=\"0.900em\" rspace=\"0.222em\">×</mo><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">T</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{x^{\\prime}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{1\\times T}</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.6\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">. </span><math id=\"S2.p1.5.m5\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"\\mathbf{x^{\\prime}}\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><msup><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">𝐱</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">′</mo></msup><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{x^{\\prime}}</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.7\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> is then encoded into </span><math id=\"S2.p1.6.m6\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"\\mathbf{z}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{d}\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">𝐳</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">∈</mo><msup><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">ℝ</mi><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">d</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{z}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{d}</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.8\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> (</span><math id=\"S2.p1.7.m7\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"d=512\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">d</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">=</mo><mn mathsize=\"0.900em\">512</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">d=512</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.9\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">), which serves as the sole input to all probes. The probes produce the predictions for single scalar attributes </span><math id=\"S2.p1.8.m8\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"\\hat{y}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{1}\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">y</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">^</mo></mover><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">∈</mo><msup><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">ℝ</mi><mn mathsize=\"0.900em\">1</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\hat{y}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{1}</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.10\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> and are trained on regression against the ground truth values </span><math id=\"S2.p1.9.m9\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"y\\in\\mathbb{R}^{1}\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">y</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">∈</mo><msup><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">ℝ</mi><mn mathsize=\"0.900em\">1</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">y\\in\\mathbb{R}^{1}</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.11\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> used during the augmentation process. The encoder is kept fully frozen: all learned parameters belong exclusively to the probe models.\nWe use the audio encoder from LAION-CLAP </span><cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\"><span id=\"S2.p1.9.12.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">[</span><a href=\"#bib.bib3\" title=\"Large-scale contrastive language-audio pretraining with feature fusion and keyword-to-caption augmentation\" class=\"ltx_ref\">33</a>, <a href=\"#bib.bib4\" title=\"HTS-at: a hierarchical token-semantic audio transformer for sound classification and detection\" class=\"ltx_ref\">2</a><span id=\"S2.p1.9.13.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">]</span></cite><span id=\"S2.p1.9.14\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> checkpoint trained on speech, music, AudioSet, and LAION-Audio-630k</span><span id=\"footnote1\" class=\"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">1</sup><span class=\"ltx_note_outer\"><span class=\"ltx_note_content\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">1</sup><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note\">1</span><span id=\"footnote1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter\">laion-clap</span>: <a href=\"https://github.com/LAION-AI/CLAP\" title=\"\" class=\"ltx_ref ltx_href\">https://github.com/LAION-AI/CLAP</a></span></span></span><span id=\"S2.p1.9.15\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">, selected for its broad coverage across audio domains.</span></p>\n<p id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1\" class=\"ltx_p\"><span id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">Loudness (LUFS).</span><span id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> Signal loudness is computed as integrated loudness following the ITU-R BS.1770 standard </span><cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\"><span id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1.3.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">[</span><a href=\"#bib.bib11\" title=\"Algorithms to measure audio programme loudness and true-peak audio level\" class=\"ltx_ref\">18</a><span id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1.4.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">]</span></cite><span id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1.5\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">, using the </span><span id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1.6\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">pyloudnorm</span><span id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1.7\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> library</span><span id=\"footnote2\" class=\"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">2</sup><span class=\"ltx_note_outer\"><span class=\"ltx_note_content\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">2</sup><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note\">2</span><span id=\"footnote2.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter\">pyloudnorm</span>: <a href=\"https://github.com/csteinmetz1/pyloudnorm\" title=\"\" class=\"ltx_ref ltx_href\">https://github.com/csteinmetz1/pyloudnorm</a></span></span></span><span id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1.8\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">. Unlike peak amplitude or RMS energy, integrated LUFS accounts for frequency-dependent loudness perception, making it the de facto standard for loudness normalization in broadcast and music production.</span></p>\n<p id=\"S3.SS1.p2.1\" class=\"ltx_p\"><span id=\"S3.SS1.p2.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">White Noise</span><span id=\"S3.SS1.p2.1.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> (100k samples) is a synthetic control of generated white noise samples of 10 seconds each with constant amplitude envelope. Since all samples share the same flat spectral shape and carry no musical or semantic content, all variation in the embeddings is driven exclusively by the applied augmentation, making it the most controlled setting in our evaluation and serving as an upper bound on what a purely acoustic signal can encode. Labels are generated synthetically as described in Sec. </span><a href=\"#S3.SS2\" title=\"3.2 Feature Generation ‣ 3 Experimental settings ‣ Probing Low-Level Acoustic Attribute Encoding in CLAP Audio Embeddings\" class=\"ltx_ref\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag\">3.2</span></a><span id=\"S3.SS1.p2.1.3\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">.</span></p>\n<p id=\"S3.SS1.p3.1\" class=\"ltx_p\"><span id=\"S3.SS1.p3.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">NSynth</span><span id=\"S3.SS1.p3.1.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> </span><cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\"><span id=\"S3.SS1.p3.1.3.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">[</span><a href=\"#bib.bib32\" title=\"Neural audio synthesis of musical notes with wavenet autoencoders\" class=\"ltx_ref\">13</a><span id=\"S3.SS1.p3.1.4.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">]</span></cite><span id=\"S3.SS1.p3.1.5\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> (306k samples) contains monophonic notes from 1,006 instruments at 16 kHz, spanning the full MIDI pitch range (21–108) at five velocity levels. Each sample is a 4-second clip in which a single note is held for three seconds and decays over the final second. It represents the simplest scenario in our evaluation, with a single note isolated from rhythmic or harmonic context.</span></p>\n<p id=\"S3.SS2.p2.3\" class=\"ltx_p\"><span id=\"S3.SS2.p2.3.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">RT60:</span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p2.3.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> A target reverberation time is uniformly sampled as </span><math id=\"S3.SS2.p2.1.m1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"t\\sim\\mathcal{U}(0.0,\\ 2.0)\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">t</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">∼</mo><mrow><mi class=\"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic\" mathsize=\"0.900em\">𝒰</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">​</mo><mrow><mo maxsize=\"0.900em\" minsize=\"0.900em\">(</mo><mn mathsize=\"0.900em\">0.0</mn><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">,</mo><mn mathsize=\"0.900em\"> 2.0</mn><mo maxsize=\"0.900em\" minsize=\"0.900em\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t\\sim\\mathcal{U}(0.0,\\ 2.0)</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S3.SS2.p2.3.3\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> s. A synthetic room impulse response (RIR) is generated using </span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p2.3.4\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">gpuRIR<span id=\"footnote3\" class=\"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">3</sup><span class=\"ltx_note_outer\"><span class=\"ltx_note_content\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">3</sup><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note\"><span id=\"footnote3.1.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">3</span></span><span id=\"footnote3.5\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">gpuRIR</span><span id=\"footnote3.6\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">: </span><a href=\"https://github.com/DavidDiazGuerra/gpuRIR\" title=\"\" class=\"ltx_ref ltx_href ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">https://github.com/DavidDiazGuerra/gpuRIR</a></span></span></span></span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p2.3.5\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">.\nFor all other datasets, a fractional pitch shift </span><math id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.m4\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"p\\sim\\mathcal{U}(-6,\\ 6)\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">p</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">∼</mo><mrow><mi class=\"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic\" mathsize=\"0.900em\">𝒰</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">​</mo><mrow><mo maxsize=\"0.900em\" minsize=\"0.900em\">(</mo><mrow><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">−</mo><mn mathsize=\"0.900em\">6</mn></mrow><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">,</mo><mn mathsize=\"0.900em\"> 6</mn><mo maxsize=\"0.900em\" minsize=\"0.900em\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p\\sim\\mathcal{U}(-6,\\ 6)</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.6\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> semitones is uniformly sampled and applied to the waveform via the </span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.7\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">torch_audiomentations<span id=\"footnote4\" class=\"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">4</sup><span class=\"ltx_note_outer\"><span class=\"ltx_note_content\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">4</sup><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note\"><span id=\"footnote4.1.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">4</span></span><span id=\"footnote4.5\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">torch_audiomentations</span><span id=\"footnote4.6\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">: </span><a href=\"https://github.com/iver56/torch-audiomentations\" title=\"\" class=\"ltx_ref ltx_href ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">https://github.com/iver56/torch-audiomentations</a></span></span></span></span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.8\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> phase vocoder. This creates a smooth distribution of pitch in all datasets, breaking the quantised structures present in music datasets (e.g. NSynth contains only integer pitch values, which we found to hinder regression performance).\nThe two strategies are not interchangeable by design: bandpass filtering is appropriate only for spectrally flat signals, while pitch shifting preserves content. Since probes are always trained and evaluated within the same dataset, no transfer across augmentation strategies is assumed or performed. In both cases, the SC is computed as defined in Sec. </span><a href=\"#S2.SS1\" title=\"2.1 Target Acoustic Attributes ‣ 2 Methodology ‣ Probing Low-Level Acoustic Attribute Encoding in CLAP Audio Embeddings\" class=\"ltx_ref\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag\">2.1</span></a><span id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.9\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> using the </span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.10\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">SpectralCentroid</span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.11\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> transform from </span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.12\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">torchaudio<span id=\"footnote5\" class=\"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">5</sup><span class=\"ltx_note_outer\"><span class=\"ltx_note_content\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">5</sup><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note\"><span id=\"footnote5.1.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">5</span></span><span id=\"footnote5.5\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">torchaudio</span><span id=\"footnote5.6\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">: </span><a href=\"https://github.com/pytorch/audio\" title=\"\" class=\"ltx_ref ltx_href ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">https://github.com/pytorch/audio</a></span></span></span></span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.13\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">, yielding a single scalar in Hz.</span></p>\n<p id=\"S4.p2.10\" class=\"ltx_p\"><span id=\"S4.p2.10.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">RT60</span><span id=\"S4.p2.10.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> is strongly and nearly linearly encoded. The Linear probe achieves\n<p id=\"S4.p3.8\" class=\"ltx_p\"><span id=\"S4.p3.8.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">LUFS</span><span id=\"S4.p3.8.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> is also strongly and approximately linearly encoded. The Linear\n<p id=\"S4.p5.15\" class=\"ltx_p\"><span id=\"S4.p5.15.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">RP</span><span id=\"S4.p5.15.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> is linearly encoded across most datasets, though with varying", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "978ba9bf-23e0-4dc1-86a9-0fe72e55523f", "uuid": "36c97cc0-712b-4547-a2b3-fbffb5e96c28", "timestamp": "2026-07-12T11:26:31.957Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "      <h5 id=\"modal-title\" class=\"modal-title\">Report GitHub Issue</h5>\n      <button type=\"submit\" value=\"internal-report\" class=\"sr-only modal-submit\">Submit without GitHub</button>\n      <button type=\"submit\" value=\"github-report\" class=\"modal-submit\">Submit in GitHub</button>\n  <a id=\"license-tr\" href=\"https://info.arxiv.org/help/license/index.html#licenses-available\">\nWithin this global picture, two encoding regimes emerge: RT60, LUFS, and RP are approximately linearly encoded, while SC requires non-linear probes.\nProbing studies of audio-language models have largely examined specific domains or model classes: early work probed speech embeddings for speaker and phonetic information </span><cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\"><span id=\"S1.p2.1.2.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">[</span><a href=\"#bib.bib36\" title=\"Probing the information encoded in x-vectors\" class=\"ltx_ref\">26</a><span id=\"S1.p2.1.3.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">]</span></cite><span id=\"S1.p2.1.4\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">, while more recent analyses of Large Audio-Language Models (LALMs), a model class that does not encompass CLAP, probe high-level perceptual attributes such as language, gender, and emotion of speech </span><cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\"><span id=\"S1.p2.1.5.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">[</span><a href=\"#bib.bib38\" title=\"AudioLens: a closer look at auditory attribute perception of large audio-language models\" class=\"ltx_ref\">35</a>, <a href=\"#bib.bib39\" title=\"Causal tracing of audio-text fusion in large audio language models\" class=\"ltx_ref\">4</a><span id=\"S1.p2.1.6.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">]</span></cite><span id=\"S1.p2.1.7\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">.\nWithin the CLAP literature, studies have shown that high-level features such as timbre </span><cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\"><span id=\"S1.p2.1.11.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">[</span><a href=\"#bib.bib22\" title=\"Do joint language-audio embeddings encode perceptual timbre semantics?\" class=\"ltx_ref\">7</a><span id=\"S1.p2.1.12.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">]</span></cite><span id=\"S1.p2.1.13\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> and emotion </span><cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\"><span id=\"S1.p2.1.14.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">[</span><a href=\"#bib.bib30\" title=\"Evaluating foundation models on timbre-related cognitive tasks\" class=\"ltx_ref\">30</a><span id=\"S1.p2.1.15.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">]</span></cite><span id=\"S1.p2.1.16\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> are effectively captured. However, low-level acoustic attributes have received far less attention.\nConversely, FXEncoder++ </span><cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\"><span id=\"S1.p2.1.20.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">[</span><a href=\"#bib.bib8\" title=\"Fx-encoder++: extracting instrument-wise audio effects representations from mixtures\" class=\"ltx_ref\">37</a><span id=\"S1.p2.1.21.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">]</span></cite><span id=\"S1.p2.1.22\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> learns representations that capture audio effects independently of content.\n<p id=\"S1.p3.1\" class=\"ltx_p\"><span id=\"S1.p3.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">These mixed findings leave a central question open: which low-level acoustic attributes are encoded in CLAP embeddings, and how readily can they be recovered?\nEach waveform </span><math id=\"S2.p1.1.m1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"\\mathbf{x}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{C\\times T}\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">𝐱</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">∈</mo><msup><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">ℝ</mi><mrow><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">C</mi><mo lspace=\"0.222em\" mathsize=\"0.900em\" rspace=\"0.222em\">×</mo><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">T</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{x}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{C\\times T}</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.3\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">, with </span><math id=\"S2.p1.2.m2\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"C\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">C</mi><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.4\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> channels and </span><math id=\"S2.p1.3.m3\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"T\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">T</mi><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.5\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> samples, is transformed with an attribute-dependent data augmentation and downmixed to mono obtaining </span><math id=\"S2.p1.4.m4\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"\\mathbf{x^{\\prime}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{1\\times T}\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">𝐱</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">′</mo></msup><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">∈</mo><msup><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">ℝ</mi><mrow><mn mathsize=\"0.900em\">1</mn><mo lspace=\"0.222em\" mathsize=\"0.900em\" rspace=\"0.222em\">×</mo><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">T</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{x^{\\prime}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{1\\times T}</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.6\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">. </span><math id=\"S2.p1.5.m5\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"\\mathbf{x^{\\prime}}\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><msup><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">𝐱</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">′</mo></msup><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{x^{\\prime}}</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.7\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> is then encoded into </span><math id=\"S2.p1.6.m6\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"\\mathbf{z}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{d}\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">𝐳</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">∈</mo><msup><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">ℝ</mi><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">d</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{z}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{d}</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.8\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> (</span><math id=\"S2.p1.7.m7\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"d=512\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">d</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">=</mo><mn mathsize=\"0.900em\">512</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">d=512</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.9\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">), which serves as the sole input to all probes. The probes produce the predictions for single scalar attributes </span><math id=\"S2.p1.8.m8\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"\\hat{y}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{1}\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">y</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">^</mo></mover><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">∈</mo><msup><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">ℝ</mi><mn mathsize=\"0.900em\">1</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\hat{y}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{1}</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.10\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> and are trained on regression against the ground truth values </span><math id=\"S2.p1.9.m9\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"y\\in\\mathbb{R}^{1}\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">y</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">∈</mo><msup><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">ℝ</mi><mn mathsize=\"0.900em\">1</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">y\\in\\mathbb{R}^{1}</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S2.p1.9.11\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> used during the augmentation process. The encoder is kept fully frozen: all learned parameters belong exclusively to the probe models.\nWe use the audio encoder from LAION-CLAP </span><cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\"><span id=\"S2.p1.9.12.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">[</span><a href=\"#bib.bib3\" title=\"Large-scale contrastive language-audio pretraining with feature fusion and keyword-to-caption augmentation\" class=\"ltx_ref\">33</a>, <a href=\"#bib.bib4\" title=\"HTS-at: a hierarchical token-semantic audio transformer for sound classification and detection\" class=\"ltx_ref\">2</a><span id=\"S2.p1.9.13.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">]</span></cite><span id=\"S2.p1.9.14\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> checkpoint trained on speech, music, AudioSet, and LAION-Audio-630k</span><span id=\"footnote1\" class=\"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">1</sup><span class=\"ltx_note_outer\"><span class=\"ltx_note_content\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">1</sup><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note\">1</span><span id=\"footnote1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter\">laion-clap</span>: <a href=\"https://github.com/LAION-AI/CLAP\" title=\"\" class=\"ltx_ref ltx_href\">https://github.com/LAION-AI/CLAP</a></span></span></span><span id=\"S2.p1.9.15\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">, selected for its broad coverage across audio domains.</span></p>\n<p id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1\" class=\"ltx_p\"><span id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">Loudness (LUFS).</span><span id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> Signal loudness is computed as integrated loudness following the ITU-R BS.1770 standard </span><cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\"><span id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1.3.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">[</span><a href=\"#bib.bib11\" title=\"Algorithms to measure audio programme loudness and true-peak audio level\" class=\"ltx_ref\">18</a><span id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1.4.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">]</span></cite><span id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1.5\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">, using the </span><span id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1.6\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">pyloudnorm</span><span id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1.7\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> library</span><span id=\"footnote2\" class=\"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">2</sup><span class=\"ltx_note_outer\"><span class=\"ltx_note_content\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">2</sup><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note\">2</span><span id=\"footnote2.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter\">pyloudnorm</span>: <a href=\"https://github.com/csteinmetz1/pyloudnorm\" title=\"\" class=\"ltx_ref ltx_href\">https://github.com/csteinmetz1/pyloudnorm</a></span></span></span><span id=\"S2.SS1.p3.1.8\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">. Unlike peak amplitude or RMS energy, integrated LUFS accounts for frequency-dependent loudness perception, making it the de facto standard for loudness normalization in broadcast and music production.</span></p>\n<p id=\"S3.SS1.p2.1\" class=\"ltx_p\"><span id=\"S3.SS1.p2.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">White Noise</span><span id=\"S3.SS1.p2.1.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> (100k samples) is a synthetic control of generated white noise samples of 10 seconds each with constant amplitude envelope. Since all samples share the same flat spectral shape and carry no musical or semantic content, all variation in the embeddings is driven exclusively by the applied augmentation, making it the most controlled setting in our evaluation and serving as an upper bound on what a purely acoustic signal can encode. Labels are generated synthetically as described in Sec. </span><a href=\"#S3.SS2\" title=\"3.2 Feature Generation ‣ 3 Experimental settings ‣ Probing Low-Level Acoustic Attribute Encoding in CLAP Audio Embeddings\" class=\"ltx_ref\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag\">3.2</span></a><span id=\"S3.SS1.p2.1.3\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">.</span></p>\n<p id=\"S3.SS1.p3.1\" class=\"ltx_p\"><span id=\"S3.SS1.p3.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">NSynth</span><span id=\"S3.SS1.p3.1.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> </span><cite class=\"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite\"><span id=\"S3.SS1.p3.1.3.1\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">[</span><a href=\"#bib.bib32\" title=\"Neural audio synthesis of musical notes with wavenet autoencoders\" class=\"ltx_ref\">13</a><span id=\"S3.SS1.p3.1.4.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">]</span></cite><span id=\"S3.SS1.p3.1.5\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> (306k samples) contains monophonic notes from 1,006 instruments at 16 kHz, spanning the full MIDI pitch range (21–108) at five velocity levels. Each sample is a 4-second clip in which a single note is held for three seconds and decays over the final second. It represents the simplest scenario in our evaluation, with a single note isolated from rhythmic or harmonic context.</span></p>\n<p id=\"S3.SS2.p2.3\" class=\"ltx_p\"><span id=\"S3.SS2.p2.3.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">RT60:</span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p2.3.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> A target reverberation time is uniformly sampled as </span><math id=\"S3.SS2.p2.1.m1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"t\\sim\\mathcal{U}(0.0,\\ 2.0)\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">t</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">∼</mo><mrow><mi class=\"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic\" mathsize=\"0.900em\">𝒰</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">​</mo><mrow><mo maxsize=\"0.900em\" minsize=\"0.900em\">(</mo><mn mathsize=\"0.900em\">0.0</mn><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">,</mo><mn mathsize=\"0.900em\"> 2.0</mn><mo maxsize=\"0.900em\" minsize=\"0.900em\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t\\sim\\mathcal{U}(0.0,\\ 2.0)</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S3.SS2.p2.3.3\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> s. A synthetic room impulse response (RIR) is generated using </span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p2.3.4\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">gpuRIR<span id=\"footnote3\" class=\"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">3</sup><span class=\"ltx_note_outer\"><span class=\"ltx_note_content\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">3</sup><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note\"><span id=\"footnote3.1.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">3</span></span><span id=\"footnote3.5\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">gpuRIR</span><span id=\"footnote3.6\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">: </span><a href=\"https://github.com/DavidDiazGuerra/gpuRIR\" title=\"\" class=\"ltx_ref ltx_href ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">https://github.com/DavidDiazGuerra/gpuRIR</a></span></span></span></span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p2.3.5\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">.\nFor all other datasets, a fractional pitch shift </span><math id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.m4\" class=\"ltx_Math\" alttext=\"p\\sim\\mathcal{U}(-6,\\ 6)\" display=\"inline\" intent=\":literal\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathsize=\"0.900em\">p</mi><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">∼</mo><mrow><mi class=\"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic\" mathsize=\"0.900em\">𝒰</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">​</mo><mrow><mo maxsize=\"0.900em\" minsize=\"0.900em\">(</mo><mrow><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">−</mo><mn mathsize=\"0.900em\">6</mn></mrow><mo mathsize=\"0.900em\">,</mo><mn mathsize=\"0.900em\"> 6</mn><mo maxsize=\"0.900em\" minsize=\"0.900em\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p\\sim\\mathcal{U}(-6,\\ 6)</annotation></semantics></math><span id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.6\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> semitones is uniformly sampled and applied to the waveform via the </span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.7\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">torch_audiomentations<span id=\"footnote4\" class=\"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">4</sup><span class=\"ltx_note_outer\"><span class=\"ltx_note_content\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">4</sup><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note\"><span id=\"footnote4.1.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">4</span></span><span id=\"footnote4.5\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">torch_audiomentations</span><span id=\"footnote4.6\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">: </span><a href=\"https://github.com/iver56/torch-audiomentations\" title=\"\" class=\"ltx_ref ltx_href ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">https://github.com/iver56/torch-audiomentations</a></span></span></span></span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.8\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> phase vocoder. This creates a smooth distribution of pitch in all datasets, breaking the quantised structures present in music datasets (e.g. NSynth contains only integer pitch values, which we found to hinder regression performance).\nThe two strategies are not interchangeable by design: bandpass filtering is appropriate only for spectrally flat signals, while pitch shifting preserves content. Since probes are always trained and evaluated within the same dataset, no transfer across augmentation strategies is assumed or performed. In both cases, the SC is computed as defined in Sec. </span><a href=\"#S2.SS1\" title=\"2.1 Target Acoustic Attributes ‣ 2 Methodology ‣ Probing Low-Level Acoustic Attribute Encoding in CLAP Audio Embeddings\" class=\"ltx_ref\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"><span class=\"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag\">2.1</span></a><span id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.9\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> using the </span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.10\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">SpectralCentroid</span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.11\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> transform from </span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.12\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_typewriter\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">torchaudio<span id=\"footnote5\" class=\"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">5</sup><span class=\"ltx_note_outer\"><span class=\"ltx_note_content\"><sup class=\"ltx_note_mark\">5</sup><span class=\"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note\"><span id=\"footnote5.1.1.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">5</span></span><span id=\"footnote5.5\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">torchaudio</span><span id=\"footnote5.6\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">: </span><a href=\"https://github.com/pytorch/audio\" title=\"\" class=\"ltx_ref ltx_href ltx_font_serif\" style=\"font-size:111%;\">https://github.com/pytorch/audio</a></span></span></span></span><span id=\"S3.SS2.p4.4.13\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">, yielding a single scalar in Hz.</span></p>\n<p id=\"S4.p2.10\" class=\"ltx_p\"><span id=\"S4.p2.10.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">RT60</span><span id=\"S4.p2.10.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> is strongly and nearly linearly encoded. The Linear probe achieves\n<p id=\"S4.p3.8\" class=\"ltx_p\"><span id=\"S4.p3.8.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">LUFS</span><span id=\"S4.p3.8.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> is also strongly and approximately linearly encoded. The Linear\n<p id=\"S4.p5.15\" class=\"ltx_p\"><span id=\"S4.p5.15.1\" class=\"ltx_text ltx_font_bold\" style=\"font-size:90%;\">RP</span><span id=\"S4.p5.15.2\" class=\"ltx_text\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"> is linearly encoded across most datasets, thou